WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.496
On Recursive Self-Improvement, Part One. By Dean W. Ball. From

00:00:01.496 --> 00:00:02.993
Hyperdimensional. America's major frontier A-I labs have begun automating large

00:00:02.993 --> 00:00:04.489
fractions of their research and engineering operations. The pace of

00:00:04.489 --> 00:00:05.985
this automation will grow during the course of twenty twenty-six,

00:00:05.985 --> 00:00:07.481
and within a year or two the effective workforces of

00:00:07.481 --> 00:00:08.978
each frontier lab will grow from the single-digit thousands to

00:00:08.978 --> 00:00:10.474
tens of thousands, and then hundreds of thousands. This means

00:00:10.474 --> 00:00:11.970
that soon, the vast majority of frontier A-I lab staff

00:00:11.970 --> 00:00:13.467
will neither sleep nor eat nor use the bathroom. They

00:00:13.467 --> 00:00:14.963
will grow smarter and more capable each month, not only

00:00:14.963 --> 00:00:16.459
because A-I itself was already improving quickly but because the

00:00:16.459 --> 00:00:17.956
only objective these hundred-thousand-strong workforces will have is to make

00:00:17.956 --> 00:00:19.452
themselves smarter. The automation of A-I research and engineering is

00:00:19.452 --> 00:00:20.948
probably the most important thing that will happen in the

00:00:20.948 --> 00:00:22.444
field of A-I over the coming year, and one of

00:00:22.444 --> 00:00:23.941
the most important things in the history of the field.

00:00:23.941 --> 00:00:25.437
But it is frustrating to talk about because it is

00:00:25.437 --> 00:00:26.933
unlikely to happen in one recognizably discrete event, and indeed

00:00:26.933 --> 00:00:28.430
in some important sense it is already happening. More frustrating

00:00:28.430 --> 00:00:29.926
still is the fact that it will take place almost

00:00:29.926 --> 00:00:31.422
entirely behind closed doors. Make no mistake: A-I agents that

00:00:31.422 --> 00:00:32.919
build the next versions of themselves are not science fiction.

00:00:32.919 --> 00:00:34.415
They are an explicit and public milestone on the roadmap

00:00:34.415 --> 00:00:35.911
of every frontier A-I lab. Open A-I has been the

00:00:35.911 --> 00:00:37.407
most transparent: they envision hundreds of thousands of automated research

00:00:37.407 --> 00:00:38.904
interns within about nine months from today, and a fully

00:00:38.904 --> 00:00:40.400
automated workforce in about two years. There is substantial uncertainty

00:00:40.400 --> 00:00:41.896
about what, exactly, automated A-I research will mean. It could

00:00:41.896 --> 00:00:43.393
simply mean that A-I capabilities progress unfolds faster, but within

00:00:43.393 --> 00:00:44.889
the familiar generative A-I paradigm. This might not matter as

00:00:44.889 --> 00:00:46.385
much as many in the A-I industry believe. It could

00:00:46.385 --> 00:00:47.881
also mean fundamental changes to the nature of A-I itself

00:00:47.881 --> 00:00:49.378
and to the strategic dynamics that obtain over the field.

00:00:49.378 --> 00:00:50.874
These are the concerns that animate the A-I twenty twenty-seven

00:00:50.874 --> 00:00:52.370
project. To be clear, though, the debate should really not

00:00:52.370 --> 00:00:53.867
be whether this automation will occur but instead about how

00:00:53.867 --> 00:00:55.363
it will occur — the details and the implications. Policymakers

00:00:55.363 --> 00:00:56.859
would be wise to take especially careful notice of this

00:00:56.859 --> 00:00:58.356
issue over the coming year or so. But they should

00:00:58.356 --> 00:00:59.852
also keep the hysterics to a minimum: yes, this really

00:00:59.852 --> 00:01:01.348
is a thing from science fiction that is happening before

00:01:01.348 --> 00:01:02.844
our eyes, but that does not mean we should behave

00:01:02.844 --> 00:01:04.341
theatrically, as an actor in a movie might. Instead, the

00:01:04.341 --> 00:01:05.837
challenge now is to deal with the legitimately sci-fi issues

00:01:05.837 --> 00:01:07.333
we face using the comparatively dull idioms of technocratic policymaking.

00:01:07.333 --> 00:01:08.830
This week, the author walks us through the range of

00:01:08.830 --> 00:01:10.326
scenarios he thinks may be possible with automated A-I research

00:01:10.326 --> 00:01:11.822
and how it may affect the dynamics of A-I development.

00:01:11.822 --> 00:01:13.319
In both pieces, there is one assumption he asks us

00:01:13.319 --> 00:01:14.815
to make, which is that substantial automation of A-I research

00:01:14.815 --> 00:01:16.311
is a near-term possibility. This requires believing a few things.

00:01:16.311 --> 00:01:17.807
First, that A-I research and engineering is substantively composed of

00:01:17.807 --> 00:01:19.304
work like: finding optimizations in various complex software systems; designing

00:01:19.304 --> 00:01:20.800
and testing experiments for A-I model training and post-training; and

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:22.296
creating software interfaces to expose A-I model capabilities to users.

00:01:22.296 --> 00:01:23.793
Second, that a great deal of this work is essentially

00:01:23.793 --> 00:01:25.289
reducible to the engineering of software. Third, that A-I models,

00:01:25.289 --> 00:01:26.785
while not yet geniuses, are reaching quite high levels of

00:01:26.785 --> 00:01:28.281
human competence. Fourth, that frontier lab leadership and staff are

00:01:28.281 --> 00:01:29.778
serious when they describe A-I research automation as a near-term

00:01:29.778 --> 00:01:31.274
goal, and that frontier lab research staff are telling the

00:01:31.274 --> 00:01:32.770
truth when they say that A-I is already writing a

00:01:32.770 --> 00:01:34.267
large fraction of their code. What Might Automated A-I Research

00:01:34.267 --> 00:01:35.763
and Engineering Be Like? Imagine yourself standing by a street

00:01:35.763 --> 00:01:37.259
and seeing a Bugatti race by you at two hundred

00:01:37.259 --> 00:01:38.756
miles per hour. A few minutes later, a second Bugatti

00:01:38.756 --> 00:01:40.252
speeds by at three hundred miles per hour. This difference

00:01:40.252 --> 00:01:41.748
in velocity is huge to anyone inside the car, and

00:01:41.748 --> 00:01:43.244
any seasoned observer of motorsport would know that a mere

00:01:43.244 --> 00:01:44.741
two hundred miles per hour is common Bugatti territory, whereas

00:01:44.741 --> 00:01:46.237
three hundred miles per hour is approaching a world record

00:01:46.237 --> 00:01:47.733
for conventional vehicle speed. But the random bystander on the

00:01:47.733 --> 00:01:49.230
street might not notice much of a difference between extremely

00:01:49.230 --> 00:01:50.726
fast and world historically fast. The current rate of A-I

00:01:50.726 --> 00:01:52.222
capabilities improvement has already surpassed the ability of most humans

00:01:52.222 --> 00:01:53.719
to keep track. It is therefore entirely possible that the

00:01:53.719 --> 00:01:55.215
automation of A-I research may lead to a dramatic acceleration

00:01:55.215 --> 00:01:56.711
in A-I capabilities advances, and that most of the public

00:01:56.711 --> 00:01:58.207
and policymakers will not really notice, especially in the early

00:01:58.207 --> 00:01:59.704
stages. The predictable result of this will be that pundits

00:01:59.704 --> 00:02:01.200
say, "those A-I hypesters promised us that this supposed A-I

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:02.696
research automation would finally mean that A-I would live up

00:02:02.696 --> 00:02:04.193
to its promises; but once again, it has just resulted

00:02:04.193 --> 00:02:05.689
in more of the same empty promises." Therefore, this scenario

00:02:05.689 --> 00:02:07.185
— call it "A-I as a normal exponentially self-improving technology"

00:02:07.185 --> 00:02:08.681
— is the bearish scenario for A-I research automation. But

00:02:08.681 --> 00:02:10.178
something else is possible, too. Imagine that instead of merely

00:02:10.178 --> 00:02:11.674
traveling one hundred miles per hour faster, the second Bugatti

00:02:11.674 --> 00:02:13.170
learned how to fly. The bystander on the street would

00:02:13.170 --> 00:02:14.667
notice the flying Bugatti not so much for its speed

00:02:14.667 --> 00:02:16.163
but for the fact that it is flying. And imagine

00:02:16.163 --> 00:02:17.659
even further that it really was the Bugatti itself that

00:02:17.659 --> 00:02:19.156
learned how to fly. The humans ostensibly at the steering

00:02:19.156 --> 00:02:20.652
wheel can explain to the public what the Bugatti did

00:02:20.652 --> 00:02:22.148
to make itself fly, but it was not ultimately their

00:02:22.148 --> 00:02:23.644
work. The Bugatti built them a joystick that operates the

00:02:23.644 --> 00:02:25.141
vehicle in flight, but again, the joystick was built by

00:02:25.141 --> 00:02:26.637
the machine rather than the humans. As our street bystander

00:02:26.637 --> 00:02:28.133
ponders this incredible feat and tries to sort his way

00:02:28.133 --> 00:02:29.630
through the millions of words written by the Bugatti explaining

00:02:29.630 --> 00:02:31.126
how it achieved flight, the Bugatti lets him know that

00:02:31.126 --> 00:02:32.622
it just figured out a way to reduce its price

00:02:32.622 --> 00:02:34.119
by ninety-nine percent. When this was a mere car, it

00:02:34.119 --> 00:02:35.615
was one of the most expensive in the world. Now

00:02:35.615 --> 00:02:37.111
it flies and costs as much as a Toyota Corolla.

00:02:37.111 --> 00:02:38.607
Oh, and the Bugatti also informs the bystander that it

00:02:38.607 --> 00:02:40.104
is pursuing a new engineering path that could allow the

00:02:40.104 --> 00:02:41.600
car to leap thirty thousand feet into the air in

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:43.096
a matter of seconds, as well as operate underwater. This

00:02:43.096 --> 00:02:44.593
is obviously a heavily stylized metaphor, but you get the

00:02:44.593 --> 00:02:46.089
idea. In one outcome, the automation of A-I engineering is

00:02:46.089 --> 00:02:47.585
hugely important yet doesn't result in a fundamental change to

00:02:47.585 --> 00:02:49.081
the dynamics of the field. In the other, something altogether

00:02:49.081 --> 00:02:50.578
new is afoot. Automated A-I Research Within the Labs. We

00:02:50.578 --> 00:02:52.074
don't know which of these scenarios describes our future more

00:02:52.074 --> 00:02:53.570
accurately. Differences in intuition about this question explain many downstream

00:02:53.570 --> 00:02:55.067
disagreements on near-future A-I capabilities and how much A-I needs

00:02:55.067 --> 00:02:56.563
to be regulated. Those with a more bearish view on

00:02:56.563 --> 00:02:58.059
A-I research automation point out that diminishing returns are common

00:02:58.059 --> 00:02:59.556
in the field. As a car picks up speed, the

00:02:59.556 --> 00:03:01.052
amount of energy required to continue accelerating increases nonlinearly. It

00:03:01.052 --> 00:03:02.548
requires about twice as much energy to accelerate from two

00:03:02.548 --> 00:03:04.044
hundred miles per hour to two hundred fifty miles per

00:03:04.044 --> 00:03:05.541
hour than it does to accelerate from one hundred miles

00:03:05.541 --> 00:03:07.037
per hour to one hundred fifty, even though the absolute

00:03:07.037 --> 00:03:08.533
quantity of acceleration — fifty miles per hour — is

00:03:08.533 --> 00:03:10.030
identical. The same dynamic often obtains in artificial intelligence. Famously,

00:03:10.030 --> 00:03:11.526
the scaling laws that appear to describe the relationship between

00:03:11.526 --> 00:03:13.022
computing power, data, and model performance suggest that order of

00:03:13.022 --> 00:03:14.519
magnitude increases in input resources yield an additional nine of

00:03:14.519 --> 00:03:16.015
reliability. In other words: for ten times more compute, you

00:03:16.015 --> 00:03:17.511
can go from nine to ninety percent, but then the

00:03:17.511 --> 00:03:19.007
next tenfold increase in compute only brings you from ninety

00:03:19.007 --> 00:03:20.504
to ninety-nine percent, and then ninety-nine to ninety-nine point nine,

00:03:20.504 --> 00:03:22.000
and so on. Very quickly, astronomical amounts of compute are

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:23.496
needed for only minuscule improvements to capability. Those who are

00:03:23.496 --> 00:03:24.993
more bullish on A-I research automation retort by observing that

00:03:24.993 --> 00:03:26.489
the field of A-I is still replete with low-hanging fruit

00:03:26.489 --> 00:03:27.985
well beyond naive scaling of resources. In particular, they point

00:03:27.985 --> 00:03:29.481
to an extremely broad set of improvements known as algorithmic

00:03:29.481 --> 00:03:30.978
efficiency. Dario Amodei has said that, with human-driven research and

00:03:30.978 --> 00:03:32.474
engineering, individual labs achieve something like four hundred percent efficiency

00:03:32.474 --> 00:03:33.970
improvements per year. Amodei describes this as a compute multiplier:

00:03:33.970 --> 00:03:35.467
the same amount of compute can deliver a model that

00:03:35.467 --> 00:03:36.963
is four times better than would otherwise be possible without

00:03:36.963 --> 00:03:38.459
the efficiency improvements. These gains come from all sorts of

00:03:38.459 --> 00:03:39.956
places: model architecture tweaks that improve how well the model

00:03:39.956 --> 00:03:41.452
learns from training data or leverage compute more effectively; improvements

00:03:41.452 --> 00:03:42.948
to training datasets that allow the model to learn more

00:03:42.948 --> 00:03:44.444
quickly; enhancements to the tooling and technical infrastructure that labs

00:03:44.444 --> 00:03:45.941
use to train and deploy models; and many other things

00:03:45.941 --> 00:03:47.437
besides. Collectively, small and medium-sized gains add up to the

00:03:47.437 --> 00:03:48.933
four hundred percent efficiency improvements Amodei describes. We know that

00:03:48.933 --> 00:03:50.430
A-I labs are bound by talent; this is why they

00:03:50.430 --> 00:03:51.926
routinely offer top-tier personnel compensation packages in the tens or

00:03:51.926 --> 00:03:53.422
hundreds of millions of dollars. For the sake of illustration,

00:03:53.422 --> 00:03:54.919
imagine that a lab has one thousand research and engineering

00:03:54.919 --> 00:03:56.415
staff, eight hundred of whom are grinding away in the

00:03:56.415 --> 00:03:57.911
search for gains within the current paradigm, and two hundred

00:03:57.911 --> 00:03:59.407
of whom are investigating new paradigms. Both do their jobs

00:03:59.407 --> 00:04:00.904
by designing and conducting experiments in an iterative fashion. In

00:04:00.904 --> 00:04:02.400
both, a huge amount of this work can be described

00:04:02.400 --> 00:04:03.896
as writing code and engineering software. This is of course

00:04:03.896 --> 00:04:05.393
an absurdly high-level description, but it is also not that

00:04:05.393 --> 00:04:06.889
hard to imagine current models automating large portions of this

00:04:06.889 --> 00:04:08.385
work. And indeed, it seems clear that they already do.

00:04:08.385 --> 00:04:09.881
Frontier lab staff now frequently say that A-I models write

00:04:09.881 --> 00:04:11.378
most or all their code. Current models are arguably already

00:04:11.378 --> 00:04:12.874
better at coding than many human researchers, particularly when considering

00:04:12.874 --> 00:04:14.370
the opportunity cost of the researchers' time. Where the models

00:04:14.370 --> 00:04:15.867
currently suffer from reliability and quality issues is in the

00:04:15.867 --> 00:04:17.363
execution of experiments over, say, several days, though they improve

00:04:17.363 --> 00:04:18.859
along these dimensions constantly. The other deficit of the models

00:04:18.859 --> 00:04:20.356
— and here they often fall down altogether — is

00:04:20.356 --> 00:04:21.852
in the generation of interesting hypotheses and research agendas. A

00:04:21.852 --> 00:04:23.348
brilliant human researcher may have some insight about a new

00:04:23.348 --> 00:04:24.844
direction of research and spend months refining his thesis, recruiting

00:04:24.844 --> 00:04:26.341
colleagues to his cause, and persuading management to allocate compute

00:04:26.341 --> 00:04:27.837
to test his ideas. Models do not tend to come

00:04:27.837 --> 00:04:29.333
up with great insights like this. But do they need

00:04:29.333 --> 00:04:30.830
to? What if instead, the brilliant human researcher had an

00:04:30.830 --> 00:04:32.326
army of automated junior researchers he could use to test

00:04:32.326 --> 00:04:33.822
his ideas in a way that would have been impossible

00:04:33.822 --> 00:04:35.319
without advanced A-I? Models could autonomously perform countless iterations on

00:04:35.319 --> 00:04:36.815
the human's fundamental experimental insight. Thus one can imagine two

00:04:36.815 --> 00:04:38.311
things happening in parallel. First, the eight hundred researchers who

00:04:38.311 --> 00:04:39.807
are grinding away within the current paradigm suddenly have vastly

00:04:39.807 --> 00:04:41.304
more bandwidth to search for more efficiency gains. An extreme

00:04:41.304 --> 00:04:42.800
outcome from this would be that labs discover dramatically more

00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:44.296
efficiency gains; it turns out there was a vast field

00:04:44.296 --> 00:04:45.793
of low-hanging fruit just waiting to be plucked, and we

00:04:45.793 --> 00:04:47.289
simply did not have enough researcher time to find it.

00:04:47.289 --> 00:04:48.785
In this world, perhaps algorithmic efficiency gains scale cleanly with

00:04:48.785 --> 00:04:50.281
the number of automated researchers: ten times the number of

00:04:50.281 --> 00:04:51.778
researchers means that annual improvements in algorithmic efficiency are four

00:04:51.778 --> 00:04:53.274
thousand percent rather than four hundred percent. But this seems

00:04:53.274 --> 00:04:54.770
unlikely. Maybe the human researchers were doing a pretty good

00:04:54.770 --> 00:04:56.267
job all along, and discovering most of the algorithmic efficiency

00:04:56.267 --> 00:04:57.763
gains that were practical to employ. In this world, perhaps

00:04:57.763 --> 00:04:59.259
automated researchers merely double the rate of improvement — eight

00:04:59.259 --> 00:05:00.756
hundred percent per year — or even worse, accelerate it

00:05:00.756 --> 00:05:02.252
by, say, twenty percent, for a final annual efficiency gain

00:05:02.252 --> 00:05:03.748
of four hundred eighty percent per year. In the most

00:05:03.748 --> 00:05:05.244
extreme bear scenario, there are literally no new gains to

00:05:05.244 --> 00:05:06.741
be discovered, so all automated researchers do is enable labs

00:05:06.741 --> 00:05:08.237
to find the same gains they would have counterfactually found

00:05:08.237 --> 00:05:09.733
with humans, but much faster. Then, at the same time,

00:05:09.733 --> 00:05:11.230
those two hundred "new paradigm" researchers suddenly have the ability

00:05:11.230 --> 00:05:12.726
to systematically investigate novel research directions with far greater velocity

00:05:12.726 --> 00:05:14.222
than is currently possible. How good are the researchers' ideas?

00:05:14.222 --> 00:05:15.719
How many novel directions are there left to pursue in

00:05:15.719 --> 00:05:17.215
deep learning, and how many of them can be pursued

00:05:17.215 --> 00:05:18.711
without the collection of new, real-world datasets? Add to this

00:05:18.711 --> 00:05:20.207
the reality that all frontier labs will bring massive new

00:05:20.207 --> 00:05:21.704
computing resources online within the coming year. These data centers

00:05:21.704 --> 00:05:23.200
are dramatically larger than anything that has come before. Remember

00:05:23.200 --> 00:05:24.696
that we have not seen any models trained on Blackwell-generation

00:05:24.696 --> 00:05:26.193
chips, and soon each lab will have hundreds of thousands

00:05:26.193 --> 00:05:27.689
of them. And the Rubin generation will begin real-world deployment

00:05:27.689 --> 00:05:29.185
in the coming months, too. There is a credible case

00:05:29.185 --> 00:05:30.681
to be made that there is a looming capabilities overhang

00:05:30.681 --> 00:05:32.178
from this alone, and that this overhang will be realized

00:05:32.178 --> 00:05:33.674
at the same time that automated A-I researchers begin to

00:05:33.674 --> 00:05:35.170
be deployed in earnest. It would therefore be wise to

00:05:35.170 --> 00:05:36.667
expect twenty twenty-six to be a more rapid year of

00:05:36.667 --> 00:05:38.163
A-I progress than all years that have come before. Indeed,

00:05:38.163 --> 00:05:39.659
this is probably the conservative forecast at this point. All

00:05:39.659 --> 00:05:41.156
of this together creates a clear picture: This year, the

00:05:41.156 --> 00:05:42.652
automation of A-I research and engineering will begin in earnest.

00:05:42.652 --> 00:05:44.148
In addition to creating at least a step-change improvement in

00:05:44.148 --> 00:05:45.644
A-I progress from its already rapid pace, this could change

00:05:45.644 --> 00:05:47.141
the dynamics of A-I competition, alter A-I geopolitics, and much

00:05:47.141 --> 00:05:48.637
more. This has been "On Recursive Self-Improvement, Part One" by

00:05:48.637 --> 00:05:50.133
Dean W. Ball, published on Hyperdimensional. You can read the

00:05:50.133 --> 00:05:51.480
full article and Part Two at hyperdimensional dot co.
